<!-- TORTURE TESTS -->
<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section section-alt" id="attacks">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Torture Tests</h2>
    <p class="lead">We tried to kill it. Here's what happened.</p>

    <div class="grid-3">
      <div class="card attack-card">
        <div class="attack-icon">&#x21BB;</div>
        <h3>Rotation Attack</h3>
        <div class="attack-result pass">SURVIVED</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Flips: perfect detection (3.3x ratio, p&asymp;10<sup>-42</sup>)</li>
          <li>Up to 7&deg; rotation: detected without position correction</li>
          <li>Full chain (rotate + flip + rotate + flip + JPEG): <strong>4.0x ratio</strong></li>
          <li>Round-trip inverse: detected despite 97.5% pixel damage</li>
          <li>Fingerprint Jaccard: 0.72 after full chain</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card attack-card">
        <div class="attack-icon">&#x2702;</div>
        <h3>Slice &amp; Stitch</h3>
        <div class="attack-result pass">SURVIVED</div>
        <ul>
          <li>Image sliced into 4 quadrants, each re-encoded JPEG Q85</li>
          <li>Individual fragments: detection breaks (too few markers)</li>
          <li>Stitched back: <strong>detection returns</strong> (3.6x, p=0.001)</li>
          <li>Stitched + JPEG Q75: still detected (3.4x, p=0.003)</li>
          <li>Stitch seams forensically visible (3.3x seam ratio)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="attack-quote">"The attack undoes itself on reassembly."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="card attack-card">
        <div class="attack-icon">&#x2922;</div>
        <h3>Scale &amp; Resize</h3>
        <div class="attack-result pass">SURVIVED</div>
        <ul>
          <li>1024px: strong detection through full cascade (3.4x&rarr;2.5x)</li>
          <li>2048px: amplifying variance ratio 3.7 &rarr; 9.3</li>
          <li>Resize to 50%, 25%, even 12%: <strong>detected</strong></li>
          <li>Resize + WebP transcoding: detected at all sizes</li>
          <li>Fingerprint Jaccard &gt;0.47 across all transforms</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fingerprint-table">
      <h3>Marker Capacity</h3>
      <p>Embedding surface scales with image resolution. Saturation stays well under 10%.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Resolution</th><th>Pixels</th><th>Markers</th><th>Saturation</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>512 &times; 512</td><td>262,144</td><td>248</td><td>6.1%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1024 &times; 1024</td><td>1,048,576</td><td>999</td><td>6.1%</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2048 &times; 2048</td><td>4,194,304</td><td>1,129</td><td>1.7%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="fingerprint-table">
      <h3>Fingerprint Stability</h3>
      <p>The disruption map &mdash; the fingerprint &mdash; survives every transform we tested. 11/11 matchable.</p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Transform</th><th>Ones</th><th>Hamming Distance</th><th>Jaccard Similarity</th><th>Matchable</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="fp-table-body">
            <tr><td>JPEG Q95 (identity)</td><td>122</td><td class="hamming-0">0.0%</td><td class="jaccard-perfect">1.000</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q85</td><td>98</td><td>13.8%</td><td>0.594</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q75</td><td>93</td><td>13.5%</td><td>0.593</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q60</td><td>105</td><td>16.5%</td><td>0.544</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q40</td><td>117</td><td>14.5%</td><td>0.604</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-separator"><td colspan="5"></td></tr>
            <tr><td>WebP Q95</td><td>139</td><td>16.5%</td><td>0.591</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>WebP Q80</td><td>90</td><td>18.7%</td><td>0.472</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>WebP Q60</td><td>96</td><td>17.2%</td><td>0.514</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr class="table-separator"><td colspan="5"></td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q85 &rarr; WebP Q80</td><td>91</td><td>17.9%</td><td>0.490</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q75 &rarr; WebP Q60</td><td>93</td><td>18.4%</td><td>0.483</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            <tr><td>JPEG Q95 &rarr; Q85 &rarr; Q75</td><td>109</td><td>15.5%</td><td>0.571</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- SCALE RESULTS -->
<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="scale">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Scale: 512 to 4096</h2>
    <p class="lead">Detection across four image sizes. Larger images mean more markers, stronger signal, deeper survival.</p>

    <h3>Capacity &amp; Cascade by Size</h3>
    <p>Full JPEG cascade (Q95 &rarr; Q85 &rarr; Q75 &rarr; Q60 &rarr; Q40) at each resolution.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Size</th><th>Markers</th><th>Gen 0 Ratio</th><th>Gen 0 p-value</th><th>Gen 4 Ratio</th><th>Gen 4 p-value</th><th>Gen 4 VarRatio</th><th>Amplifies</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>512 &times; 512</td><td>236</td>
            <td>0.6&times;</td><td>1.00</td>
            <td>0.6&times;</td><td>1.00</td>
            <td>2.41</td><td>KS only</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>1024 &times; 1024</td><td>676</td>
            <td>1.1&times;</td><td>9.8e-2</td>
            <td>1.1&times;</td><td>8.9e-2</td>
            <td>3.84</td><td class="yes">YES</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2048 &times; 2048</td><td>691</td>
            <td>1.3&times;</td><td>2.9e-4</td>
            <td>1.2&times;</td><td>3.0e-2</td>
            <td>3.77</td><td class="yes">YES</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="highlight-row">
            <td>4096 &times; 4096</td><td>591</td>
            <td>1.6&times;</td><td>8.7e-7</td>
            <td>1.4&times;</td><td>4.2e-4</td>
            <td>5.22</td><td class="yes">YES</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>4096 &rarr; Resize Survival</h3>
    <p>Embed at 4096, resize down, re-encode. The signal follows the content, not the resolution.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Target</th><th>Scale</th><th>Ratio</th><th>p-value</th><th>VarRatio</th><th>Detected</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>2048px</td><td>0.50&times;</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>3.8e-7</td><td>2.40</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1024px</td><td>0.25&times;</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>1.1e-6</td><td>1.12</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
          <tr><td>512px</td><td>0.12&times;</td><td>1.7&times;</td><td>7.7e-9</td><td>&mdash;</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
          <tr><td>256px</td><td>0.06&times;</td><td>1.8&times;</td><td>3.5e-9</td><td>&mdash;</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>4096 &rarr; Resize + Re-encode</h3>
    <p>The real-world pipeline: resize then re-encode to JPEG or WebP. Every combination detected.</p>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div>
        <h4>JPEG Re-encode</h4>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Target</th><th>Quality</th><th>Ratio</th><th>p-value</th><th></th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>Q85</td><td>1.5&times;</td><td>4.8e-6</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>Q75</td><td>1.5&times;</td><td>4.9e-6</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>Q60</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>3.7e-6</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>Q85</td><td>1.5&times;</td><td>5.9e-6</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>Q75</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>4.0e-6</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>Q60</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>7.7e-7</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4>WebP Transcode</h4>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Target</th><th>Quality</th><th>Ratio</th><th>p-value</th><th></th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>WQ95</td><td>1.7&times;</td><td>3.9e-8</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>WQ80</td><td>1.6&times;</td><td>3.3e-7</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>1024px</td><td>WQ60</td><td>1.7&times;</td><td>5.2e-9</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>WQ95</td><td>1.7&times;</td><td>4.5e-8</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>WQ80</td><td>1.8&times;</td><td>4.5e-10</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
              <tr><td>512px</td><td>WQ60</td><td>1.7&times;</td><td>5.3e-9</td><td class="yes">YES</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- FIVE LAYERS -->
<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section section-alt" id="layers">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Five Detection Layers</h2>
    <p class="lead">Defense in depth. Each layer operates independently in a different domain, with a validated operational range. Together they compound.</p>

    <div class="layers">
      <div class="layer">
        <div class="layer-num">A</div>
        <div class="layer-body">
          <h3>DQT Prime Tables</h3>
          <p>Replace JPEG quantization table entries with nearest primes. The table itself is the provenance signal. Container-level detection. <strong>Operational: G0 only</strong> &mdash; by design, the container signal does not survive re-encoding.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer">
        <div class="layer-num">BC</div>
        <div class="layer-body">
          <h3>Compound Frequency Markers</h3>
          <p>Twin-prime markers at known positions. Detection compares prime-gap hit rate at marker vs. control positions in the same image. Compound strategies collapse false positive probability. <strong>Operational: G0&ndash;G2</strong> &mdash; frequency signal degrades under aggressive compression. 96.4% G-B detection at Q95, not reliable past Q60.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer">
        <div class="layer-num">D</div>
        <div class="layer-body">
          <h3>Blind Spatial Variance</h3>
          <p>KS test on local spatial variance and channel-difference variance distributions. The image is its own control group. No reference image needed. Compression <em>amplifies</em> the signal &mdash; the adversary who compresses to destroy the frequency signal is constructing the spatial variance detection signal. <strong>Operational: G0&ndash;G4</strong> &mdash; 90%+ blind detection at Q40 on 500 images. This is the paper.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer">
        <div class="layer-num">E</div>
        <div class="layer-body">
          <h3>Spanning Relational Sentinel</h3>
          <p>Mersenne-prime anchors with correlated flanking pixels within 8&times;8 DCT blocks. The differential between positions survives when absolute values do not. Tiered detection (24/16/8-bit) degrades gracefully at block boundaries. <strong>Operational: G0&ndash;G4</strong> &mdash; 98.6% manifest survival at Q40, &gt;99% effective at any tier. Validated on 500 images.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="layer">
        <div class="layer-num">F</div>
        <div class="layer-body">
          <h3>Rare Basket / Attribution</h3>
          <p>Position pattern derived from 256-bit key via HMAC-SHA512. Enables attribution through Jaccard similarity at corpus scale. The fingerprint, not the signal. Payload encoder (structured flanking data: creator ID, timestamp, section index) is architecturally ready but not yet validated at scale.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<!-- UNIVERSALITY -->
<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section section-alt" id="universal">
  <div class="container">
    <h2>Beyond JPEG</h2>
    <p class="lead">The fuse is engineering. The fire is physics.</p>
    <p>Any codec that uses a <strong>partition &rarr; transform &rarr; quantize</strong> pipeline is susceptible. The mechanism is universal:</p>

    <div class="grid-3">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Images</h3>
        <p>JPEG, WebP, HEIF &mdash; all use block-based DCT or wavelet quantization. Tested and confirmed across JPEG and WebP with cross-codec transcoding.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Audio</h3>
        <p>MP3, AAC, Opus &mdash; frequency-domain quantization in sub-band partitions. Initial MP3 testing has exceeded expectations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Video</h3>
        <p>H.264, H.265, AV1 &mdash; block-based motion-compensated DCT quantization. The same thermodynamic tax applies per-frame.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

